==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*weba-'', from Indo-European ''*webh-'' ‘weave, braid’.  Germanic cognates include Old Frisian [[weva]], Middle Low German [[weven|wēven]] (Dutch [[weven]]), Old High German [[weban]] (German [[weben]]), Old Norse [[vefa]] (Swedish [[väva]]).  The IE root is also the source of Sanskrit [[उभ्ढाित]] ‘entwine’, Greek {{polytonic|[[ὑφαινειν]]}} ‘weave’.  [[webbian|Webbian]], as well as modern English [[web]] and [[wasp]], are related.

